79
00:04:44,896 --> 00:04:46,077
Rebecca Morgan.

80
00:04:46,077 --> 00:04:47,414
A 30-year-old waitress.

81
00:04:47,414 --> 00:04:49,527
Stabbed to death in her 
rowhouse in Mayfair.

82
00:04:49,527 --> 00:04:50,545
No weapon recorvered.

83
00:04:50,545 --> 00:04:52,455
Got some prints, hair, but never a match.

84
00:04:52,455 --> 00:04:54,065
Lady was butchered real good.

85
00:04:54,065 --> 00:04:55,267
Gaping neck wound.

86
00:04:55,267 --> 00:04:57,685
Three-year-old Sean sat 
with her all night like that.

87
00:04:57,685 --> 00:04:59,413
No wonder he's a little s.o.b.

88
00:04:59,413 --> 00:05:00,787
Who found the body?

89
00:05:00,787 --> 00:05:02,988
Neighbor. Leon Kincaid.

90
00:05:02,988 --> 00:05:06,213
Up early for a jog, heard 
the kid wailing, called 911.

91
00:05:06,213 --> 00:05:07,173
Suspects?

92
00:05:07,173 --> 00:05:10,741
She worked as a cocktail waitress
at a joint called Boilermakers.

93
00:05:10,741 --> 00:05:12,302
Ton of interviews from there.

94
00:05:12,302 --> 00:05:15,076
Patrons, co-workers--- nothing stuck.

95
00:05:15,076 --> 00:05:16,421
Jeffries is running the names again.

96
00:05:16,421 --> 00:05:19,506
Maybe 15 years later someone's 
true colors have come through.

97
00:05:19,506 --> 00:05:21,419
Anything on Sean's father?

98
00:05:21,419 --> 00:05:23,554
The assigned's notebook says 
he was never in the picture.

99
00:05:23,554 --> 00:05:26,063
No next of kin, landing Sean in foster care...

100
00:05:26,063 --> 00:05:28,540
leaving us with red and yellow balloons,

101
00:05:28,540 --> 00:05:31,574
a train and the name Bobby.

102
00:05:31,574 --> 00:05:34,956
Pretty modest starting point.

103
00:05:34,956 --> 00:05:36,206
Any luck for us?

104
00:05:36,206 --> 00:05:41,047
Yeah. Your 911 caller, Leon Kincaid,
the guy's on the books.

105
00:05:41,314 --> 00:05:42,399
What'd he do?

106
00:05:42,399 --> 00:05:46,136
Well, starting in '91, been arrested 
for open lewdeness, loitering,

107
00:05:46,136 --> 00:05:49,721
and my personal favorite, 
prowling at night.

108
00:05:49,721 --> 00:05:52,349
Any idea where Leon 
hangs out these days?

109
00:05:52,349 --> 00:05:57,241
Yeah, he happens to be the top man
at the Germantown Dorsett Bank.

110
00:06:04,934 --> 00:06:06,975
Leon Kincaid?

111
00:06:07,333 --> 00:06:09,504
Detectives Rush and Valens. 
Can we have a minute?

112
00:06:09,504 --> 00:06:11,629
Um... Okay.

113
00:06:11,629 --> 00:06:12,947
I'll be right back, Jodie.

114
00:06:12,947 --> 00:06:14,439
This way.

115
00:06:15,731 --> 00:06:16,762
About 6:00 a.m.

116
00:06:16,762 --> 00:06:19,656
I'm out running and hear 
the kid bawling his head off,

117
00:06:19,656 --> 00:06:21,278
so I go aroung the back

118
00:06:21,278 --> 00:06:24,443
and look in, and, uh... 
it was just awful.

119
00:06:24,443 --> 00:06:26,204
Did you know Rebecca?

120
00:06:26,430 --> 00:06:28,595
Enough to say hello, that's about it.

121
00:06:28,595 --> 00:06:30,921
Ever see anyone go in 
or out of her house?

122
00:06:30,921 --> 00:06:32,103
Nah.

123
00:06:32,103 --> 00:06:34,127
Pretty girl, right?

124
00:06:34,922 --> 00:06:36,036
I guess.

125
00:06:36,036 --> 00:06:38,068
Ever ask her out?

126
00:06:38,931 --> 00:06:42,562
Like I said, we never really spoke, so, uh...

127
00:06:42,562 --> 00:06:44,722
I'm sorry, I'm not much help.

128
00:06:44,722 --> 00:06:46,565
Uh, but I should get back.

129
00:06:46,565 --> 00:06:48,154
To Jodie?

130
00:06:48,562 --> 00:06:49,385
Pardon?

131
00:06:49,385 --> 00:06:53,460
Need to get back so he can look over 
her shoulder, down her blouse.

132
00:06:53,460 --> 00:06:54,990
Busty girl.

133
00:06:54,990 --> 00:06:56,701
We know about you, Leon.

134
00:06:56,701 --> 00:06:59,624
We know you've had your 
trouble with boundaries.

135
00:06:59,624 --> 00:07:00,955
I never hurt anyone.

136
00:07:00,955 --> 00:07:02,619
I never touched.

137
00:07:02,619 --> 00:07:05,070
Did my probation, got counseling.

138
00:07:05,070 --> 00:07:06,326
Good for you.

139
00:07:06,326 --> 00:07:08,556
But in '89, you were just getting revved up.

140
00:07:08,556 --> 00:07:11,691
Hey, Leon, you registered 
as a sex offender?

141
00:07:11,691 --> 00:07:14,081
No, hell no. I never molested anyone.

142
00:07:14,081 --> 00:07:16,406
Still, maybe I'll talk to sex 
crimes see what we can do

143
00:07:16,406 --> 00:07:17,673
about getting you on the books.

144
00:07:17,673 --> 00:07:19,679
Yeah, 'cause this sheep 
dresses up real good.

145
00:07:19,679 --> 00:07:20,922
Better get the word out.

146
00:07:20,922 --> 00:07:24,608
Oh, jeez, okay. Okay.

147
00:07:26,486 --> 00:07:29,876
I'd peep on Rebecca.

148
00:07:30,390 --> 00:07:32,267
Pretty regular?

149
00:07:32,531 --> 00:07:33,878
Yeah.

150
00:07:33,878 --> 00:07:36,589
How about the night she died?

151
00:07:37,549 --> 00:07:39,651
But I didn't kill her.

152
00:07:46,899 --> 00:07:48,642
Ned, is something wrong?

153
00:07:48,998 --> 00:07:51,178
I wanted to apologize for earlier.

154
00:07:51,178 --> 00:07:52,902
You don't have to say anything.

155
00:07:52,902 --> 00:07:54,453
Just...

156
00:07:54,702 --> 00:07:57,122
well, the ball's in your court, okay?

157
00:07:57,122 --> 00:07:58,892
Okay. Thank you.

158
00:07:58,892 --> 00:08:00,928
One more thing.

159
00:08:04,896 --> 00:08:05,866
What's all this?

160
00:08:05,866 --> 00:08:08,626
For Sean, for his birthday.

161
00:08:08,626 --> 00:08:10,651
Hey, these are for you, little man.

162
00:08:10,651 --> 00:08:11,595
There you go.

163
00:08:11,595 --> 00:08:13,546
Ned, don't give him any gifts.

164
00:08:13,546 --> 00:08:15,921
Oh, every boy needs something 
to open on his birthday.

165
00:08:15,921 --> 00:08:17,499
We have cake, that's enough.

166
00:08:17,499 --> 00:08:18,703
Oh, here.

167
00:08:18,703 --> 00:08:20,392
This is gonna be just like the Pampers.

168
00:08:20,392 --> 00:08:22,843
Oh, no, no, no. 
I take back what I said earlier.

169
00:08:22,843 --> 00:08:25,807
I've written everything down.
I'm going to write you a check.

170
00:08:25,807 --> 00:08:28,483
What, so it can bounce?

171
00:08:31,223 --> 00:08:32,369
Here you go.

172
00:08:38,936 --> 00:08:40,628
Red and yellow balloons.

173
00:08:40,628 --> 00:08:42,699
Like Sean remembered.

174
00:08:42,699 --> 00:08:44,868
So, Leon, that's all you saw?

175
00:08:45,183 --> 00:08:48,237
I wasn't exactly pumped to stick around
for a three-year-old's birthday party.

176
00:08:48,237 --> 00:08:49,913
Right. No girl coming out of cake.

177
00:08:49,913 --> 00:08:52,561
Where's the upside for the 
guy standing in the hedge?

178
00:08:52,561 --> 00:08:56,133
At least my move wasn't handling 
out Pampers and balloons.

179
00:08:56,133 --> 00:08:59,935
This Ned guy's a complete stooge.

180
00:09:02,933 --> 00:09:04,394
Ned Ryan.

181
00:09:04,394 --> 00:09:06,829
The write-up here says you 
told the assigned detective

182
00:09:06,829 --> 00:09:09,467
you hadn't seen Rebecca in over a week.

183
00:09:09,467 --> 00:09:10,868
Been so long now.

184
00:09:10,868 --> 00:09:14,046
I couldn't tell you when 
I talked to Rebecca last.

185
00:09:14,046 --> 00:09:16,093
Well, how about the night 
she was murdered?

186
00:09:16,093 --> 00:09:16,457
No.

187
00:09:16,457 --> 00:09:19,697
Ned, we know you were at Rebecca's
shortly before it happened.

188
00:09:19,697 --> 00:09:22,160
And you came bearing gifts; balloons.

189
00:09:22,160 --> 00:09:25,796
So don't lie about it like you 
did the first time around.

190
00:09:26,625 --> 00:09:29,094
Maybe... I was there.

191
00:09:29,094 --> 00:09:31,459
But I left after a few minutes.

192
00:09:31,459 --> 00:09:32,967
But you were angry, right?

193
00:09:32,967 --> 00:09:34,247
So maybe you did a U-turn.

194
00:09:34,247 --> 00:09:37,596
Yeah, 'cause you and Rebecca 
fought earlier that day, too.

195
00:09:38,227 --> 00:09:40,233
Rebecca was a regular at the store.

196
00:09:40,233 --> 00:09:43,461
I felt bad for her-- struggling 
to support Sean on her own.

197
00:09:43,461 --> 00:09:44,779
You were giving her Pampers.

198
00:09:44,779 --> 00:09:49,847
Yes, I'd slip her Pampers, 
baby food-- to cut her a break.

199
00:09:50,303 --> 00:09:52,019
Thanks so much, Ned.

200
00:09:52,019 --> 00:09:52,855
Not a problem.

201
00:09:52,855 --> 00:09:55,440
I just added another shift at the tavern,

202
00:09:55,440 --> 00:09:57,956
so it won't be long before 
I'm on my own two feet.

203
00:09:57,956 --> 00:10:00,753
I wish you were working 
less at that bar, not more.

204
00:10:00,753 --> 00:10:03,692
A woman like you in such a filthy place...

205
00:10:03,692 --> 00:10:04,995
it's not right.

206
00:10:04,995 --> 00:10:08,407
Well, you're a doll, but it's a real 
blessing to have more work.

207
00:10:08,407 --> 00:10:10,189
Thanks again, Ned.

208
00:10:10,756 --> 00:10:12,496
Oh, Ned...

209
00:10:12,970 --> 00:10:14,969
Oh, Ned, I'm sorry.

210
00:10:14,969 --> 00:10:18,652
I'm just not the kind of gal who 
casually necks with a man.

211
00:10:18,652 --> 00:10:21,519
Rebecca, I didn't mean it like that.

212
00:10:21,519 --> 00:10:23,055
I would like to kiss you,

213
00:10:23,055 --> 00:10:26,812
because what I have to say 
is anything but casual.

214
00:10:26,812 --> 00:10:28,601
But you barely know me.

215
00:10:28,601 --> 00:10:30,634
My folks dated one 
evening at a county fair

216
00:10:30,634 --> 00:10:33,333
to know that they would spend 
the next 51 years together.

217
00:10:33,333 --> 00:10:34,235
Oh, Ned.

218
00:10:34,235 --> 00:10:35,721
You need a man in the house.

219
00:10:35,721 --> 00:10:37,726
A father figure to Sean.

220
00:10:37,726 --> 00:10:41,082
There's already a man in my life.

221
00:10:41,413 --> 00:10:42,951
What?

222
00:10:44,037 --> 00:10:45,159
Who?

223
00:10:45,159 --> 00:10:46,574
And where is he?

224
00:10:46,574 --> 00:10:50,002
He's from before -- back in Virginia.

225
00:10:50,002 --> 00:10:52,718
Well, how could he allow 
you to be here alone?

226
00:10:52,718 --> 00:10:53,999
It's just all mixed up.

227
00:10:53,999 --> 00:10:55,775
It's upside-down.

228
00:10:56,153 --> 00:10:57,992
I'm sorry, Ned.

229
00:10:57,992 --> 00:11:02,508
This just isn't proper airing 
these personal matters.

230
00:11:04,548 --> 00:11:07,077
I guess I would have figured 
it all out soon enough, huh?

231
00:11:07,077 --> 00:11:08,696
Yeah, Sean's three today.

232
00:11:08,696 --> 00:11:12,116
I guess he won't be needing 
boxes and boxes and boxes

233
00:11:12,116 --> 00:11:14,905
of Pampers too much longer!

234
00:11:19,369 --> 00:11:20,872
So you felt rejected.

235
00:11:20,872 --> 00:11:24,803
No, no, no. I felt horrible 
for blowing up like that.

236
00:11:25,083 --> 00:11:30,431
And that night, when I goofed 
again, I left... for good.

237
00:11:30,431 --> 00:11:32,269
Where were you the rest of the night?

238
00:11:32,269 --> 00:11:34,742
I lived in an apartment building at the time.

239
00:11:34,742 --> 00:11:38,208
Whether anyone saw me, 
can vouch for me, I wouldn't know.

240
00:11:38,208 --> 00:11:39,531
Okay, Ned.

241
00:11:39,531 --> 00:11:40,618
We'll look into it.

242
00:11:40,618 --> 00:11:45,328
I just wanted to find a gal like 
my mother... from a better time.

243
00:11:45,806 --> 00:11:48,599
Rebecca was that girl.

244
00:11:53,560 --> 00:11:55,275
Ned's story checks out.

245
00:11:55,275 --> 00:11:56,913
An old coot at the Tree Lane Apartment

246
00:11:56,913 --> 00:11:58,800
knew all about his pining for Rebecca.

247
00:11:58,800 --> 00:12:00,301
What, he see him the night of the murder?

248
00:12:00,301 --> 00:12:02,413
Coot says Ned was on his 
balcony for hours that night

249
00:12:02,413 --> 00:12:04,641
letting balloons go one by one.

250
00:12:04,641 --> 00:12:06,740
Time to shift focus to this man in her life.

251
00:12:06,740 --> 00:12:08,606
Well, maybe the man in 
her life was Sean's dad.

252
00:12:08,606 --> 00:12:09,791
Maybe that was Bobby.

253
00:12:09,791 --> 00:12:10,310
Got something?

254
00:12:10,310 --> 00:12:11,641
Autotracked Rebecca Morgan

255
00:12:11,641 --> 00:12:14,637
looking for that connection back in Virginia.

256
00:12:15,161 --> 00:12:17,173
Rebecca Morgan...

